DecisionTree and Random Forest Model¶

In this model, we are trying to select several features from our price datasets and find out if there is a relationship between these features and the ultimate prices. We are going to use the DecisionTree model to construct a random forest model to solve this problem.

The first step is feature selection. Considering that the flucuation and the value of the previous prices may affect the future ones, we included the rolling standard deviation and rolling mean of the previous 5 day's prices as our feature. We are going to use these two features as our input variable and to predict the price, which is the output variable.

Since we are going to drop the NaN values, we cannot use the dataframe of the combined prices df. Instead, we are going to use df_gold and df_bit, separately.

In [175]:
# Features construction 
df_gold['pct_change_gold'] = df_gold['gold'].pct_change()
df_bit['pct_change_bit'] = df_bit['bit'].pct_change()

df_gold['std_5_gold'] = df_gold['pct_change_gold'].rolling(5).std()
df_bit['std_5_bit'] = df_bit['pct_change_bit'].rolling(5).std()

df_gold['std_30_gold'] = df_gold['pct_change_gold'].rolling(30).std()
df_bit['std_30_bit'] = df_bit['pct_change_bit'].rolling(30).std()

df_gold['ret_1_gold'] = df_gold['pct_change_gold'].rolling(1).mean()
df_bit['ret_1_bit'] = df_bit['pct_change_bit'].rolling(1).mean()

df_gold['ret_5_gold'] = df_gold['pct_change_gold'].rolling(5).mean()
df_bit['ret_5_bit'] = df_bit['pct_change_bit'].rolling(5).mean()

df_gold['ret_30_gold'] = df_gold['pct_change_gold'].rolling(30).mean()
df_bit['ret_30_bit'] = df_bit['pct_change_bit'].rolling(30).mean()

df_gold['max_5_gold'] = df_gold['pct_change_gold'].rolling(5).max()
df_bit['max_5_bit'] = df_bit['pct_change_bit'].rolling(5).max()

df_gold['max_30_gold'] = df_gold['pct_change_gold'].rolling(30).max()
df_bit['max_30_bit'] = df_bit['pct_change_bit'].rolling(30).max()

df_gold['min_5_gold'] = df_gold['pct_change_gold'].rolling(5).min()
df_bit['min_5_bit'] = df_bit['pct_change_bit'].rolling(5).min()

df_gold['min_30_gold'] = df_gold['pct_change_gold'].rolling(30).min()
df_bit['min_30_bit'] = df_bit['pct_change_bit'].rolling(30).min()

df_gold.dropna(inplace=True)
df_bit.dropna(inplace=True)

# X is the input variable
X_gold = df_gold[['ret_1_gold', 'std_5_gold', 'ret_5_gold', 'std_30_gold', 'ret_30_gold']]
X_bit = df_bit[['ret_1_bit', 'std_5_bit', 'ret_5_bit', 'std_30_bit', 'ret_30_bit']]

# Y is the target or output variable
y_gold = np.where(df_gold['gold'].shift(-1) > df_gold['gold'], 1, -1)
y_bit = np.where(df_bit['bit'].shift(-1) > df_bit['bit'], 1, -1)

Train-test split¶

In [ ]:
# Total dataset length
dataset_length_gold = df_gold.shape[0]
dataset_length_bit = df_bit.shape[0]

# Training dataset length
split_gold = int(dataset_length_gold * 0.75)
split_bit = int(dataset_length_bit * 0.75)
In [ ]:
# Splitiing the X and y into train and test datasets
# gold
X_train_gold, X_test_gold = X_gold[:split_gold], X_gold[split_gold:]
y_train_gold, y_test_gold = y_gold[:split_gold], y_gold[split_gold:]

# bit
X_train_bit, X_test_bit = X_bit[:split_bit], X_bit[split_bit:]
y_train_bit, y_test_bit = y_bit[:split_bit], y_bit[split_bit:]
In [ ]:
# Training the machine learning model
clf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=5)

# Create the model on train dataset
model_gold = clf.fit(X_train_gold, y_train_gold)
model_bit = clf.fit(X_train_bit, y_train_bit)
In [ ]:
# Report the accuracy score of our two models
print('Correct Prediction (%) for gold:', accuracy_score(y_test_gold, model_gold.predict(X_test_gold), normalize=True)*100.0)
print('Correct Prediction (%) for bit:', accuracy_score(y_test_bit, model_bit.predict(X_test_bit), normalize=True)*100.0)

The prediction of gold is 50.814% and the prediction of bitcoin is 52.339%, which is optimal. Next we are going to see the expected return these models predict.
